I think the issue here is what constitutes "alive" and how to keep it "alive" after a long period of inactivity. Up until now fully lab-grown life has only been in the cell or muscle stage. Whatever constitutes the "spark of life" has largely evaded scientists up to now. Problem is, us humans are fragile. One organ failure leads to a cataclysmic domino effect where everything goes to hell, and that "spark" goes away. Current cryo techniques effectively induce total body shutdown making it only good for storing cells for long-term preservation with no hope of revival. An ideal cryo system merely puts the body into a hyper-coma that leaves the systems needed to maintain the "spark" on while supplying the body with the baseline nutrients needed to be "functional".

Anonymous Sat 24 Feb 2018 03:55:37 No.14217991 Report

>>14217619
Has anyone gotten close to explaining what consciousness is yet? I'm sure most people would agree that the single-celled organisms we evolved from have no sense of consciousness. Yet, along the path we evolved consciousness either for some purpose or just as a by-product of something else. I would say that if you imagine human beings as organic computational machines, taking input and producing output based on the current input and past experience, then there isn't really a need for the concept of "consciousness." Yet, I'm sure most everybody would claim that they have awareness of the things happening to them. I've heard some people say that it's just your disconnected observation of data passing through your brain, that you have no free will and you're just observing the operation of your meat computational processes. I've also heard that it's just your brain building an internal model of the world based off of your experience and your current information, which would explain its role in evolution. In the end you could probably say your consciousness is just a quirk of a remarkably unlikely arrangement of particular atoms at a given point in time. But that might be overly nihilistic and close-minded. Humans like to think they understand the world when we aren't even close to understanding anything fundamental about the universe and many problems are too complex to think about in a given human lifetime.

To try and be slightly less nihilistic, the conclusion I came to was the ability to be self aware our own existence and enact on that self awareness is what sets apart "consciousness" from being meatbags able to make fancy computations being fueled by bodily desires. I can say no to wanting food, even though I might be hungry, or I can say no to wanting to bang people even when the brain's being internally drugged by hormones demanding otherwise, or yes to jumping out of that airplane 10,000 ft in the air. We can also look at of that and go "Why?".
This seems to be part of the inevitable outcome of having a brain capable of problem solving, with a increased ability to do so, we eventually start problem solving ourselves directly.
To the last point, only morons think we understand everything about the universe we exist in. We know a fair deal about it, and went and recorded it down so we didn't have to start from square one every lifetime, but that hardly constitutes everything. We're learning new things all the time, and with new things being created constantly there's no way to ever know everything.
The supposed "lack of free will" can only hypothetically exist in in linear 4D space, the second the ability to meaningfully change our location in said 4D space will we be able to say for certain one way or the other.
